## 🏠 1. LAN — Local Area Network

**Scope:** Single building, office floor, small campus. Defined by **proximity**.

### Core Principles
- High bandwidth, low latency (short distances)
- Shared resources (printers, servers, internet)
- Privately owned/managed by one org — full control
- Ethernet is the dominant technology

### Design Constraints
- **Physical cabling** — distance limits before signal degradation
- **Cost** — lower than MAN/WAN but still real for larger orgs
- **Scalability limits** — broadcast domains, IP exhaustion (without subnetting), management complexity
- **Security** — internal threats (insiders, compromised devices) + external perimeter breaches

### Operational Tradeoffs
- Performance vs cost (better cabling/switches = higher price)
- Simplicity vs features (unmanaged vs managed switches)
- Security vs accessibility (restriction vs productivity)

### Core Components

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| **NICs** | Connect devices to the network |
| **Cabling** | Cat5e/6/6a/7 copper, or fiber (longer runs, higher speed, EMI-immune) |
| **Switches** | Layer 2 — forward frames by MAC address |
| **Routers** | Layer 3 — forward packets by IP, connect subnets/internet |
| **WAPs** | Wireless connectivity |

### Switch Types
- **Unmanaged** — plug-and-play, no config, good for small/simple nets
- **Managed** — VLANs, QoS, port mirroring, SNMP monitoring — needed for larger/complex LANs

### Topology Options

| Topology | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Star** | Most common — all devices to central switch; easy to manage; single-cable failure isolated; switch failure = segment down |
| **Tree (hierarchical)** | Multiple stars off a backbone — scales across floors/buildings |
| **Mesh (full/partial)** | Every device (or subset) connects to every other — highly redundant, expensive for wired; common in wireless mesh |

### Segmentation Concepts
- **Collision domain** — per-switch-port in modern Ethernet (was whole segment with hubs)
- **Broadcast domain** — not segmented by switches, only by routers; large broadcast domains = congestion risk
- **VLANs** — logically segment a physical LAN (e.g. HR, Engineering, Finance, Guest Wi-Fi) → smaller broadcast domains, better security isolation, better performance

### Speed & Duplex
- Speeds: 10/100 Mbps → 1/10/40/100 Gbps
- **Half-duplex** — one direction at a time (older, collision-prone)
- **Full-duplex** — simultaneous send/receive — standard today

**Example — 20-person office:** Star topology, 24-port Gigabit managed switch, Cat 6 cabling, firewall/router to modem, WAP for wireless; single VLAN or +1 guest VLAN; Gigabit full-duplex.

