## 🏙️ 2. MAN — Metropolitan Area Network

**Scope:** A city or large metro region — **interconnects multiple LANs**.

### Core Principles
- Links geographically dispersed LANs (e.g. multiple branches in one city)
- Historically higher bandwidth than WAN links (shorter distances)
- Often uses shared/public infra (ISP fiber) or private enterprise infra
- Frequently built/managed by ISPs/telcos who lease capacity

### Design Constraints
- **Cost** of laying fiber or leasing high-capacity lines — much higher than LAN
- **Distance/signal integrity** — needs fiber + transmission equipment (multiplexers, DWDM)
- **Interoperability** — diverse LAN technologies need common standards
- **Security** — data crosses public/shared infra; securing inter-site links is critical

### Operational Tradeoffs
- Bandwidth vs cost
- Control (own infra) vs reliance on providers (cheaper, but dependence/vendor lock-in)
- Reliability/redundancy vs added complexity and cost

### Core Components

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| **Fiber optic cabling** | Backbone — high bandwidth, long distance |
| **High-performance routers** | Direct traffic between LANs/external nets |
| **High-capacity switches** | Used in POPs and segment interconnects |
| **DWDM (multiplexers)** | Multiple data streams over one fiber via different light wavelengths |
| **Metro Ethernet** | ISP-provided Ethernet connectivity across a metro area |
| **SONET/SDH** | Older carrier-grade fiber transport standards |

### Topology Options

| Topology | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Ring** | Historically common (SONET rings); traffic reroutable if a break occurs |
| **Hub-and-spoke** | Simple but single point of failure at the hub |
| **Partial mesh** | More resilient, some redundant paths |

### Other Concepts
- **Aggregation** — MAN collects LAN traffic, funnels toward WAN/other MAN segments via POPs
- **SLAs** — define guaranteed uptime, bandwidth, latency, packet loss when using a provider

**Example — university campus:** Fiber ring backbone linking buildings, star LANs inside each building, Metro Ethernet for inter-building speed, DWDM on trunk lines.

