## 🌍 3. WAN — Wide Area Network

**Scope:** Countries/continents. **The internet is the prime example.**

### Core Principles
- Global connectivity, breaks down geographic barriers
- **Packet switching** — data broken into packets, routed independently, reassembled at destination
- "Network of networks" — connects LANs and MANs together
- Dominated by telcos/ISPs who own the underlying infra (undersea cables, satellites, terrestrial fiber)

### Design Constraints
- **Cost** of long-distance links — inherently high
- **Latency** — physical distance is a fundamental, non-eliminable constraint
- **Bandwidth limitations** — more expensive/less available than LAN bandwidth
- **Complexity** — multiple providers, diverse tech, complex routing
- **Security** — most challenging landscape; data crosses untrusted networks; encryption/auth non-negotiable

### Operational Tradeoffs
- Cost vs performance (satellite = cheap/high-latency; dedicated fiber = expensive/low-latency)
- Reliability vs cost (redundant links from multiple providers = $$$)
- Control vs outsourcing (own global WAN is prohibitively expensive for most)
- Security vs usability (VPNs/encryption add overhead)

### Core Components

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| **Routers** | Primary devices connecting disparate networks |
| **Leased lines** (T1/E1, T3/E3) | Dedicated point-to-point, expensive, reliable, guaranteed bandwidth |
| **MPLS** | Label-based traffic engineering; private WAN, prioritization, VPN services |
| **VPNs** | Secure private connections over public networks — **IPsec** (encrypt/auth IP traffic) or **SSL/TLS** (secure remote access) |
| **Broadband internet** | DSL/Cable/Fiber — for less critical links or backup |
| **Satellite links** | Remote locations, high latency |
| **Cellular/mobile data** | Backup or temporary connectivity |
| **Modems/CSU-DSUs** | Digital↔analog conversion for certain WAN line types |
| **Firewalls** | Perimeter security at WAN connection points |

### Topology Options

| Topology | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Point-to-point** | Simple two-location link |
| **Hub-and-spoke** | Central site + branches — common for corporate WANs |
| **Full mesh** | Every site to every site — highly redundant, very expensive/complex |
| **Partial mesh** | Balance of redundancy and cost |

### Routing Protocols
- **IGPs** (Interior Gateway Protocols) — within one autonomous system, e.g. OSPF, EIGRP
- **EGPs** (Exterior Gateway Protocols) — between autonomous systems, e.g. **BGP** — the internet's core routing protocol

### Traffic Engineering & QoS
- Prioritize time-sensitive traffic (VoIP, video conferencing) over less critical (file transfers)
- MPLS/dedicated circuits offer better QoS guarantees than public internet VPNs

**Example — multinational corp (NY HQ, London, Tokyo, Mumbai):** Hub-and-spoke with partial mesh; NY↔London high-bandwidth MPLS/dedicated fiber; NY↔Tokyo/Mumbai MPLS or robust IPsec VPN; enterprise routers + firewalls at every site; QoS for voice/video.

